# Summary
This unit explores React context architectures, rendering triggers, and internal state batching updates to optimize rendering performances.

## Context API
React Context provides a way to pass data through the component tree without having to pass props down manually at every level (Prop Drilling).

$$\text{Prop Drilling: } \text{Parent} \rightarrow \text{Child} \rightarrow \text{Grandchild} \rightarrow \text{LeafComponent}$$
$$\text{Context: } \text{Provider} \rightarrow \text{LeafComponent} \text{ (Direct access)}$$

* **Provider Node**: Holds data state and publishes values.
* **Consumer Hook (`useContext`)**: Subscribes to provider value updates.

### Context Triggers & Re-rendering
When a provider value updates, **all** components that consume that context will re-render, even if they are wrapped in `React.memo`! To avoid excessive updates:
1. Split contexts into distinct state and dispatcher contexts.
2. Wrap components carefully or compute derived states with `useMemo`.

---

## State Batching Mechanics
Batching is when React groups multiple state updates into a single re-render for better performance.

### React 18 Automatic Batching
In React 18+, all updates (including promises, setTimeouts, native event handlers) are batched automatically.

```javascript
function handleMultipleUpdates() {
  // Triggered concurrently
  setCount(c => c + 1);
  setFlag(f => !f);
  // React triggers exactly ONE re-render at the end of stack
}
```

### Functional State Updater Rules
If state updates depend on previous values, always use functional state updaters to prevent reading stale closure values:

```javascript
// INACCURATE: count is closed over, updates may collide
setCount(count + 1);
setCount(count + 1);

// ACCURATE: Reads latest state parameter from update queue
setCount(c => c + 1);
setCount(c => c + 1);
```
